I just screamed and ran out of the room. Neighbors were breakfasting, heading to work or asleep in bed when an explosion at a military barracks turned their homes to rubble and they were confronted with the sight of bodies being carried away. There was a terrific crash which reminded me of the Blitz. After that, the ceiling started to fall down around me, said Joan Betteridge, a pensioner in the southern England town of Deal, where the blast at the Royal Marines School of Music occurred. From the wrecked, smoke-clouded barracks, I could hear terrified screams of agony. 